{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641898"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:33:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:33:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17911"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17911"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.19,0.03,0.13,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10625"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76897"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10625"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17911"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62402"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24754"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24757"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76897"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAlmost 1.9 million Australians have diabetes. More than 300 Australians develop diabetes every day.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors is a contributor to insulin resistance in type 2 diabetes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased hepatic glucose production","Improved glucose tolerance","Enhanced beta cell function","Increased insulin sensitivity","Hyperinsulinaemia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperinsulinaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a contributor to insulin resistance in type 2 diabetes. It occurs as the body attempts to compensate for insulin resistance by producing more insulin, which can further exacerbate the resistance over time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased insulin sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E is the opposite of insulin resistance and would not contribute to the condition. In fact, increased sensitivity would improve glucose uptake and utilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced beta cell function\u003C/strong\u003E would lead to better insulin production and regulation, which is not a characteristic of type 2 diabetes. In this condition, beta cell dysfunction is more common.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased hepatic glucose production\u003C/strong\u003E would help in managing blood glucose levels, as the liver would release less glucose into the bloodstream. In type 2 diabetes, increased hepatic glucose production is often a problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImproved glucose tolerance\u003C/strong\u003E indicates better control of blood sugar levels and is not a contributor to insulin resistance. Impaired glucose tolerance is a feature of type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Insulin resistance in type 2 diabetes is influenced by multiple factors including hyperinsulinaemia, beta cell dysfunction, and impaired glucose tolerance.","Understanding the pathophysiology of type 2 diabetes is crucial for effective management and treatment strategies."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288","Galicia-Garcia U, Benito-Vicente A, Jebari S, Larrea-Sebal A, Siddiqi H, Uribe KB, Ostolaza H, Mart\u00edn C. Pathophysiology of Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus. Int J Mol Sci. 2020 Aug 30;21(17):6275. doi: 10.3390/ijms21176275. PMID: 32872570; PMCID: PMC7503727","Banday MZ, Sameer AS, Nissar S. Pathophysiology of diabetes: An overview. Avicenna J Med. 2020 Oct 13;10(4):174-188. doi: 10.4103/ajm.ajm_53_20. PMID: 33437689; PMCID: PMC7791288","Diabetes Australia. Diabetes in Australia [Internet]. Diabetes Australia. 2024. Available from: https://www.diabetesaustralia.com.au/about-diabetes/diabetes-in-australia/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62402"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17911"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62402"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T19:06:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T19:06:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10625"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76897"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","syno